{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"684fdb5b-a223-44b4-b65f-f549f776aaca","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump. Here are your main options:\n\n**1. `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform, easiest)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n**2. WinDbg** (Windows, most powerful) — load with SOS extension (`!analyze -v`)\n\n**3. LLDB + SOS** (Linux/macOS)\n\nWould you like help running `dotnet-dump analyze` on a specific file, or do you need guidance on a particular aspect of the analysis (e.g., exceptions, deadlocks, memory)?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c3fe5ba-4ecc-42b5-a96d-402dca17d28e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET app. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for \"Configure and collect crash dumps\" and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":341,"requestId":"5031:41344:27E5C3:321C86:69F5558A"},"id":"34cd4a56-58a9-4454-8053-8fd8df132034","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:38:29.026Z","parentId":"70b33527-fb18-44ed-a81b-c40183232865"}
